eople and their parents, Reczek and Bosley-Smith explore the powerful ties that bind families together, for better or worse. They show us why many feel obliged to maintain even troubled—and sometimes outright toxic—relationships with their parents. They argue that this relationship persists because what we think of as the “natural” and inevitable connection between parents and adult children is actually created and sustained by the sociocultural power of compulsory kinship. After revealing what holds even the most troubled intergenerational ties together, Families We Keep gives us permission to break free of those family bonds that are not in our best interests.Reczek and Bosley-Smith challenge our deep-rooted conviction that family—and specifically, our relationships with our parents—should be maintained at any cost. Families We Keep shines a light on the shifting importance of family in America, and how LGBTQ people navigate its complexities as adults.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDysfunctional families. 0aParent and adult child. 0aParent and child. 0aSexual minoritiesxFamily relationships. 0aSexual minorities' families. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aAdult Children.  aAlternative Families.  aCloseness.  aCloset.  aCompulsory Kinship.  aConflict Work.  aDad’s Closet.  aDisclosure.  aDoing Family.  aEducation.  aEstrangement.  aFamily Conflict.  aFamily Work.  aFamily.  aGrowth.  aHomophobia.  aIntergenerational Ties.  aIt Gets Better.  aKin Work.  aLGBTQ Adults.  aLGBTQ Families.  aLGBTQ.  aLiberation.  aLoss.  aLove.  aMarriage.  aNormalization.  aParenthood.  aParents.  aQueer.  aRug.  aTacit Knowledge.  aTrans closet.  aTransphobia.  aUniqueness.  aWhiteness.1 aBosley-Smith, Emma, eauthor.4aut4ht